post_text: Tekamah-Herman has qualified for a USDA program to provide free breakfasts and lunches for all students. The free program will be in effect retroactively from September 1, 2020 through the end of the first semester. Any charged meals between September 1 and today have been refunded to your student's lunch account. Going forward, all main meals will be free, but students will still be charged for ala carte items and extra milk.

post_text:
There are two events for Tiger Athletics today. Our softball team travels to Fort Calhoun and our volleyball team plays their jamboree game in Humphrey. If you do not already have a ticket for the jamboree game in Humphrey, you will not be allowed in.

The guidelines for the softball game in Fort Calhoun are as follows:
-Masks are required upon entry of the game. Once spectators are in their area and can socially distance, mask are then optional.
-Both home and away spectators will enter through southwest gate entrance
-Home spectators will occupy left to center field
-Away spectators will occupy center to right field (Please walk the warning track around left field to get to open seating area
-Areas will be roped off
-Please bring blankets, chairs, etc. for seating; bleachers will not be provided
-Masks are required to use the Portable Restrooms
-A portable restroom will be used for home and away spectators
-Away Fans: Portable is located in the northeast corner of the facility

Good luck, Tigers!!

Here are the protocols for the softball game in Ashland-Greenwood on Thursday, August 20th:
· Family members only.
· Families are expected to sit together. We will not ask for a spectator list but will use the honor system. Any K – 12 students should be sitting with their family.
· All spectators are encouraged to wear a mask.
· Social distancing is expected outside of family groups
· There will be no bleachers, fans will need to bring chairs and stay on the visitor’s side of the field.
· No concessions. Please do not bring sunflower seeds or peanuts into the ball complex.
· At the conclusion of the game please exit in a timely manner.

**Reminder, protocols are set by the host school on a per game basis**

With COVID conditions changing frequently, we will be posting guidelines for each athletic event a day or two prior to the competition. The guidelines will be set by the school hosting the competition. Attached are the current guidelines for the softball jamboree tomorrow, August 18th.

The following practices are being followed by coaches and student-athletes at Tekamah-Herman Public Schools:
• Equipment (Helmets, Gloves, etc.) is not shared and is used by one individual for the entire season
• Equipment is being disinfected daily.
• Score tables are limited to required personnel only.
• All team benches are limited to players, coaches, trainer, and team managers.

*People should self-monitor for symptoms based off of CDC guidelines. Stay home if warranted.

Just a couple reminders for all students who intend to participate in athletics for the 2020-2021 school year:

-ALL athletes must have the NSAA & Insurance/Permission to Treat forms signed by a parent or guardian.
-ONLY 7th graders, 9th graders, and students who did not participate in a sport during the 2019-2020 school year, must have a physical prior to participating.

All physicals must be turned in prior to the first day of practice. Athletes who are required to have physicals, will not be allowed to practice without a physical. The NSAA and Insurance/Permission to Treat forms must be turned in prior to the first competition. If you have any questions, please contact Athletic Director Zach Rosenboom at zrosenboom@thtigers.org.

post_text:
Dear Parents,

I hope your summer is going well. We have been working hard on planning for the challenges we will face as we move closer to having students back at school in August. A core group of educators and board members have been working on the aspects that will go into next school year. Included in our plans are scenarios in which 100% of students will be on campus in the fall, 50% of our students on campus and a final scenario would be remote learning for all of our students.

We would like you to take a few moments to fill out a parent survey so we can get your input as we finalize our plans. Plans will be published at the end of July or the first part of August.

To take the survey click on the link provided. The Survey will close July 10th at 11:59 PM. Your input is greatly appreciated.

https://nasb.sjc1.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_8f8jIjdduwpL6jr

Dan Gross
Superintendent

The summer strength & conditioning program will begin on Monday, June 1st. Athletes will be lifting/conditioning Monday, Tuesday, and Thursday mornings. All high school boys, plus junior high AND high school girls will workout from 7-8AM. Junior high boys will workout from 8:30-9:30AM.

The first week (June 1st) will take place outside at the track and field house. Junior high and high school girls will begin at the track at 7AM, while high school boys will begin at the field house at 7AM. Junior high boys will begin at the field house at 8:30AM. We will transition to the school the following week.

ALL athletes must have a signed waiver prior to participating in the conditioning program. The waiver can be picked up from the high school, or can also be found on the school website or at the following link: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1dJ_WQAod6RZVPHN-XmHfs0_L9Jxo6juF/view?usp=sharing

Completed waivers can be returned to the high school office, a coach, or emailed to cklein@esu2.org.

The first week (June 1st) will take place outside at the track and field house. Junior high and high school girls will begin at the track at 7AM, while high school boys will begin at the field house at 7AM. Junior high boys will begin at the field house at 8:30AM. We will transition to the school the following week.

ALL athletes must have a signed waiver prior to participating in the conditioning program. The waiver can be picked up from the high school, or can also be found on the school website or at the following link: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1dJ_WQAod6RZVPHN-XmHfs0_L9Jxo6juF/view?usp=sharing

Completed waivers can be returned to the high school office, a coach, or emailed to cklein@esu2.org.

Tekamah- Herman FFA Chapter
May 20 at 5:21 PM ·

Highlights of our 2019 FFA year! I am so proud of each and every one of you. I know that this year did not go as planned, from having class and meetings on the stage to rescheduling LDE's to cancelling state because of Covid 19. Your hard work and passion for agriculture does not go unnoticed and we are building a great chapter. I miss each of you and hope you have a fantastic summer!

To My Seniors- You guys will never truely understand how much you mean to me. Without you Tekamah-Herman FFA would not be half of what it is. You guys have been through so much, 2 teacher changes, classroom transtions, and now Covid... I can't even begin to explain the important role each of you played in getting the Ag Program through those transitions. Each of you are going to do absolutely incredible things in the next coming years, and I cannot wait to hear all about it. Don't forget where you come from and know I BELIEVE in each of you.

Miss Zabel

post_text:
Due to the Covid-19 virus Tekamah-Herman Schools will be closed for the next two weeks. Updates will be coming in the form of mass emails and social media in the days ahead. It is time to start practicing Social Distancing in our community for the good of those in our community who are most susceptible and our health care professionals who take care of all us.

Social distancing is a non-pharmaceutical intervention employed to slow the spread of a contagious disease. If we can slow the spread we give our health care workers and facilities a chance to manage the situation without overwhelming them. Stay home as much as you can.
